WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:17.760
Hi, folks. Thank you. So I'm Amelia McNamara. I tweet at AmeliaMN and I just tweeted out

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:22.240
a link to these slides if you want to follow along. There's lots of references and links

00:00:22.240 --> 00:00:27.760
there. So the most important thing that you need to get away from my talk is that the

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:35.599
dress has pockets. But I had a few other things that I wanted to say about how I thought

00:00:35.599 --> 00:00:40.160
this project sort of related to open source development. So I have some lessons learned.

00:00:40.160 --> 00:00:47.200
So one is to build on existing resources. I used hex stickers from RStudio mainly. These

00:00:47.200 --> 00:00:52.360
are licensed with the CC0 license. So I was able to use them and I found hexes from a

00:00:52.360 --> 00:01:00.320
few other sources. And here's the list. It was sort of arbitrarily chosen. And then you

00:01:00.320 --> 00:01:05.239
need to use your skills. So once I had the hex stickers, I needed to array them in such

00:01:05.239 --> 00:01:09.800
a way that it made a pattern that I could have printed on fabric. And you may not know

00:01:09.800 --> 00:01:14.120
this about me, but I went to design school for a year. So I know how to use Adobe Illustrator.

00:01:14.120 --> 00:01:18.599
And so I spent lots of time painstakingly moving these images around so that the left

00:01:18.599 --> 00:01:22.839
hand side lined up perfectly with the right hand side and the top with the bottom. And

00:01:22.839 --> 00:01:27.040
then I was able to upload this image to the website Spoonflower and get some custom fabric

00:01:27.040 --> 00:01:33.120
sewn. And then the other skill that I used is that I know how to sew. And if you don't

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:36.839
sew, you might not know that there's a difference between two kinds of fabric. There's woven

00:01:36.839 --> 00:01:41.320
fabric and knit fabric. Woven fabric is what like a regular button down shirt would be

00:01:41.320 --> 00:01:45.360
made out of. It's not stretchy. It's not as comfortable. And you can sew it on a regular

00:01:45.360 --> 00:01:49.239
sewing machine. Knit fabric is what they make T-shirts out of. It's stretchy. It's

00:01:49.239 --> 00:01:53.239
comfy. It feels like you're wearing pajamas. But you need some special tools or skills

00:01:53.239 --> 00:01:57.199
to sew it. So if you're going to work with woven material, you probably want to use a

00:01:57.199 --> 00:02:01.760
regular sewing machine, which has one thing of thread and a single needle. If you are

00:02:01.760 --> 00:02:07.239
going to work with knit fabric, you probably need a serger or an overlock machine.

00:02:07.239 --> 00:02:12.080
And then I found that this quote, which I can't find the source for, but I remember

00:02:12.080 --> 00:02:15.679
Hadley Wickham saying something like, once you have the data in the right format, the

00:02:15.679 --> 00:02:20.080
visualization is trivial. I found that once I had the pieces of the dress cut out, sewing

00:02:20.080 --> 00:02:24.160
the dress was trivial. So getting everything so that it was right side up and was going

00:02:24.160 --> 00:02:28.080
to line up nicely, that was the hardest part. And then I was able to just put it together.

00:02:28.080 --> 00:02:32.600
If you're using a serger, you use that to make seams. And if you look at the inside

00:02:32.600 --> 00:02:37.520
of a T-shirt, like the RStudio Conf T-shirt, it looks like a nice bound edge. And then

00:02:37.520 --> 00:02:41.339
I've got a picture of the seam from my dress there as well. The reason why it looks so

00:02:41.339 --> 00:02:45.220
nice is the serger has a knife as part of it. So as you run the material through, it

00:02:45.220 --> 00:02:49.259
cuts off the excess and then it binds it all together. This works for the inside seams

00:02:49.259 --> 00:02:53.419
and to put pieces together, but it does not work for hems. So if you look at a professionally

00:02:53.419 --> 00:02:58.539
made knit garment, like the RStudio Conf T-shirt, it has been used, they've used a cover stitch

00:02:58.539 --> 00:03:02.600
machine or a cover hem machine to put it together. I don't have access to a cover hem machine,

00:03:02.600 --> 00:03:06.139
so I had to do the hems on my regular sewing machine with twin needles. It didn't turn

00:03:06.139 --> 00:03:08.740
out as nice as I would have liked.

00:03:08.740 --> 00:03:13.059
And the next lesson is to document your work. I tweeted about this project once I had done

00:03:13.059 --> 00:03:16.839
it and I was glad to have some beautiful photos taken by my best friend, who calls herself

00:03:16.839 --> 00:03:21.500
my Instagram husband. Then I also blogged about this project. So if you want to know

00:03:21.500 --> 00:03:26.399
more about how I did it, you can go find that on my blog. And then you need to also share

00:03:26.399 --> 00:03:31.259
your work. So I put the Adobe Illustrator file up on GitHub as well as the JPEG. So

00:03:31.259 --> 00:03:34.580
if you want to download it, modify it, upload it to Spoonflower and make your own creation,

00:03:34.580 --> 00:03:39.080
you can. You can also just go to Spoonflower and I sell the material there. You could get

00:03:39.080 --> 00:03:43.740
it printed on a woven fabric, like a cotton or a canvas, and many people have done this.

00:03:43.740 --> 00:03:47.699
So I started a thread on Twitter, which is a bunch of people who have made things. Some

00:03:47.699 --> 00:03:52.820
of these people are here and I think they are amazing. If you're not as crafty, but

00:03:52.820 --> 00:03:57.699
you want some stuff like this for your own home, you could go on Spoonflower and they

00:03:57.699 --> 00:04:04.000
sell like a bedspread with the hexes all over it and a tablecloth. And again, people have

00:04:04.000 --> 00:04:07.800
purchased some of these things. You could go to Redbubble, they have some clothes, although

00:04:07.800 --> 00:04:12.600
not as nice as my custom dress, obviously. Zazzle has things like tote bags and sneakers.

00:04:12.600 --> 00:04:16.320
Someone bought the sneakers. I get like a dollar kickback when you buy something like

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:21.600
this. So there's links in the slideshow. And then the last lesson is that you should leverage

00:04:21.600 --> 00:04:25.799
your community. So I just wanted to give a shout out to Danny Kaplan. He was the one

00:04:25.799 --> 00:04:29.119
who told me that I shouldn't make all the hexes at full opacity, that it would be more

00:04:29.119 --> 00:04:33.799
interesting if many of them were lighter colored. My mom, who taught me how to sew, let me use

00:04:33.799 --> 00:04:38.480
her serger and also reminded me about pockets on dresses. And then my best friend, Alex,

00:04:38.480 --> 00:04:40.440
who took all the beautiful photos. Thanks.

